{"cursor":"4600","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox Historic building |name=Arg |image=Defense.gov photo essay 110604-D-XH843-\n036.jpg |caption=The Afghan flag flies over the entrance to the palace of Afghan\nPresident Hamid Karzai in Kabul, Afghanistan, June 4, 2011. |map_type=\n|latitude= |longitude= |location_town=Kabul |location_country=Afghanistan\n|architect= |client= |engineer= |construction_start_date=1880 |date_demolished=\n|cost= |structural_system= |style= |size=Approximately 83 acres }}\n\nThe 'Arg' (meaning citadel in Persian and Pashto) serves as the presidential\npalace in Kabul, Afghanistan. http://president.gov.af/en/page/1050# It\nsits on an 83 acres wide area in the Wazir Akbar Khan section of the city, near\nthe international embassies and Afghan ministries. The Arg was built after the\ndestruction of the Bala Hissar in 1880 by the British Indian troops. It has been\nused by many Afghan kings and presidents, from King Abdur Rahman Khan to the\ncurrent President Hamid Karzai.\n","linknr":195,"url":"Arg_(Kabul)","recorded":1362666283,"links":21,"instances":[],"pdf":[],"categories":["Buildings and structures in Kabul","Official residences in Afghanistan","Presidential palaces"],"headings":["History","See also","Gallery","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ed/Defense.gov_photo_essay_110604-D-XH843-036.jpg/220px-Defense.gov_photo_essay_110604-D-XH843-036.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3c/Barack_Obama_and_Hamid_Karzai_bilateral_meeting_in_Kabul_May_1%2C_2012.jpg/120px-Barack_Obama_and_Hamid_Karzai_bilateral_meeting_in_Kabul_May_1%2C_2012.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/65/Defense.gov_photo_essay_110709-F-RG147-311.jpg/120px-Defense.gov_photo_essay_110709-F-RG147-311.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Defense.gov_photo_essay_110604-D-XH843-035.jpg/120px-Defense.gov_photo_essay_110604-D-XH843-035.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.o